The Pencil Case (pencil box) is able to hold a maximum of 9 unsharpened pencils. It has an 8" ruler on the side. The Pencil door slides up through a slot in the bottom of the box to keep the pencils from falling out. And includes a notch to help with the removing of the door. The pencil topper is an adapter that allows the user to use mechanical pencil replacement erasers with a normal pencil. As an added extra,there is also a compass that is used to make circles ranging in 1/2" intervals from 1/2-5". All of these parts can be stored in their own slots that have been designed into the pencil box. The pencil topper and compass slots have grooves in them to improve accessibility of the objects.

I designed the box and then incorporated a ruler into it. I then performed some calculations to find the highest quantity of pencils that I could fit into as small of a space as possible and still have clearance. I then made the door, compass and pencil topper. I then spent a few days critiquing my idea and improving the design and appearance. Followed by renderings.

description.text:
This is a very quick and basic lampshade inspired by banana leaves. The leaves are a single layer (0.25mm) thick so will require a well-adjusted printer! The centre part has a 30mm hole to fit a B22 batten (not sure about E27 sorry - I don't have one to try it on). The centre has slots to fit either 5, 7 or 9 leaves at regular spacing around the perimeter.

How to make it:
-Print one centre part, preferably using NO extra shells as the holes will be too small otherwise, and 15% fill (or whatever you prefer)
-Print 5, 7 or 9 leaves. 3 will work also, just use every 3rd hole of the top row
-Carefully fit the base of leaf stem into appropriate hole in centre part
-Attach to light fitting
-NOTE: SUITABLE FOR CFL OR LED LAMPS ONLY!

You may have issues getting the leaf stem bases to fit in the holes - either file/sand them slightly or file out the hole with a square needle file (3mm or smaller) Ideally the stems should press in snugly until the flange touches the base part.

The leaves print flat, but will sag under their own weight. The amount of sag will depend on your specific filament. I made two lampshades while developing the design, the first used translucent green PLA for the leaves, the second used aluminium, copper and brass metal-fill (see pics). The green PLA sagged a lot; the metal-fill didn't sag as much.

I may make adjustments to the design depending on how my shades fare. I'm happy with them so far, but I'll probably think of improvements later on...

This is a wireless tank level monitor I threw together for monitoring our house rain water tank level which is about 60m up the hill from the house. It runs on a couple of arduino pro mini's and uses a ultrasonic sensor to detect the water level. The components are as "cheap as chips" and is a bit of fun to put together.
It consists of a solar powered transmitter which sits on top of the water tank and senses the water level, then converts it to % full. This is then transmitted to a hand held receiver which, when the button is pushed, displays the water level %.

Battery holders are a 4xAA and 4xAAA flex holder. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:456900

Electronics

You will need:
2 x arduino pro mini's http://www.ebay.com.au/itm/191736125295?_trksid=p2057872.m2749.l2649&ssPageName=STRK%3AMEBIDX%3AIT
Ultrasonic sensor http://www.ebay.com.au/itm/New-HC-SR04-Ultrasonic-Module-Distance-Transducer-Sensor-For-Arduino-Robot-/151747147831?hash=item2354d5b837:g:qacAAOxy~g5RwndA
1 x pair transmitter and receiver module http://www.ebay.com.au/itm/271455682908?_trksid=p2057872.m2749.l2649&ssPageName=STRK%3AMEBIDX%3AIT
2 x Buck converters http://www.ebay.com.au/itm/271968342012?_trksid=p2057872.m2749.l2649&ssPageName=STRK%3AMEBIDX%3AIT
1 x 16x2 lcd http://www.ebay.com.au/itm/1pcs-New-LCD-Display-Module-LCM-blue-blacklight-Character-1602-16x2-HD44780-/271969080313?hash=item3f529ed3f9:g:SYgAAOSwVupTmAJC
1 x 10k trim pot and a 220k resistor.
99mm x 89mm 6v solar panel.
Some strip board or veroboard or protoboard to put it together.

The Tx is straight forward. The Trigger pin of HC-SR04 goes to pin 10 of pro mini while the echo pin goes to pin 9. The data pin of the radio Tx goes to pin 12 of pro mini. All power is routed through a buck converter set to 5v to the pro mini, HC-SR04 and radio Tx. The reason for the buck coverter is because the HC-SR04 reportedly has a max voltage of 5.5v so might as well run everything off the buck. I also added a 99mm x 89mm 6v solar panel which I already had lying around. If you cannot find one this size, either design your own mount or let me know the sizes and I will draw one for you.
Female header pins are used under the Pro Mini so it can easily be removed for uploading sketches.
You will need to download the radiohead library for the arduino ide before you can upload the sketches.
The Receiver is a wee bit more complicated but still easy to understand. Just look at the jpg of the veroboard layout for how I put it together.
I used 4 x AAA batteries for the RX and used a momentary push button switch on the battery + . Just press and hold the button until pro mini boots and you get a reading.
Of course you are welcome to make any changes you want as this is just how I wanted it set up and may not suit you.

description.text:
A basic but (IMO) quite attractive fern leaf/frond lampshade. The leaf is a single layer (0.25mm) thick so will require a well-adjusted printer! The centre part has slots for assembly with 5, 7 or 9 leaves - you choose how many you want!

I designed it with very thin leaves so they will move in a breeze and look more realistic; as a bonus they are quick to print (~12 mins for one, 22 mins for two) and very filament-frugal.

It also makes pretty shadows on the ceiling! Check out the photos to see the difference between a small clear LED and a large diffused LED.

I have included a file with one leaf, and another with two leaves for easier printing if your printer is big enough.

How to make it:
-Print one centre part, preferably using NO extra shells as the holes will be too small otherwise, and 15% fill (or whatever you prefer)
-Print 5, 7 or 9 leaves. 3 will work also, just use every 3rd hole of the top row
-Carefully fit the base of leaf stem into appropriate hole in centre part
-Attach to light fitting
-NOTE: SUITABLE FOR CFL OR LED LAMPS ONLY!

You may have issues getting the leaf stem bases to fit in the holes - either file/sand them slightly or file out the hole with a square needle file (3mm or smaller) Ideally the stems should press in snugly until the flange touches the base part.

Because the leaves are thin they will sag under their own weight. The amount of sag will depend on your specific filament. The prototype lampshade was made from aluminium-fill PLA with a black PLA centre part. The aluminium filament is a bit stiffer than ordinary PLA so your results may vary. I may update the design later depending on feedback.

The leaf shape was made by 3D Builder from a vector image then edited in 123D Design; the centre was made from scratch in 123D Design

This moon rover is pretty simple; the real point is the treads.  The idea of turning my Stretchy Bracelet into tank tracks is thanks to BenRockhold.  Turns out it works really well: if you push this around on a slightly grippy surface like carpet, the tracks roll easily.
In fact, the track keys into the wheels so well, this could probably be used as a timing belt or chain.

Print the parts list (use multiply on the wheels and wheelpegs).  For the tracks, turn off fill entirely so it just prints the perimeter.  The rover body wants to warp (the slices are strain reliefs, but they only help so much).  Mine worked fine even though the body was warped, but this might be a good application for PLA.  On the other hand, I'm not sure how well the tracks will function without the pliability of ABS.  
The OpenSCAD file is parameterized so you can play around with different track dimensions.  Ten points to anyone who posts a derivative with a cooler-looking rover body.

The power of 3d printing over traditional molding is that you can create a unique object everytime.

the one in thingiverse may be a bit outdated The new source includes a shell script to generate infinite unique boxes, I recommend you to try it :) Selected as participant at Maker Faire Rome, 3d printing contest!

It allows you to scan bigger objects but you sometimes need to manually align a single scan if the software doesn't align it properly.
You need to confirm each scan before you can move onto the next, unlike auto scan mode with the turtable which does a full 360° scan in one click.

Here is a simple electronics box for the Sanguinololu board (were all the connections actually fit inside the box). When I built my Huxley I had a perfect box for the electronics. This is a replication of that box. I am only using the lid myself after deciding that 10mm holes for ventilation would be enough to keep the stepper drivers cool. On the original lid I had a fan mounted.
I had to split the box in half because my Huxley can only print 130X130mm.
The box is 144x82mm and 29mm deep (outside measured). Walls about 2mm.
The extra slit on the lid is for the SD-Card reader. That's the position I have my reader in. But you can of course move it around in SketchUp.
Print 2 of each part (lid and bottom) and use the "Joins" to snap the box parts together using the 10mm holes, then use 4 M3X40 screws and 4 M3 nuts to assemble the lid and the bottom parts together.

remixed_from.title: 9 camera GoPro Action Camera 360 rig (with underwater case)

description.text:
I have modified this rig to provide 6 gopro camera's around the center of the rig, and two gopro's which will be angled up. Gopro's are mounted in their waterproof housing.

The 8 gorpo's are required because when you are recording underwater, the field of view get's reduced by about 33% - enough reduction to no longer make your video's overlap, thus not stitchable on a traditional rig like the freedom 360, or even gopro's new omni.

There are two mounts on the camera - one external classic gopro mont (underwater selfie stick holder), and one 1/4 classic tripod mount.

I've used this for aerial photography on my drone. you can see an early video here: https://vr.gopro.com/video/201c92ba737ccd314f782280dd1d4a88

I will be testing the rig in Cancun in the beginning of June, and will post the video.

Edited last rig in tinkercad to add second gorpo connection, and the tripod mount.

you can "tinker" this yourself here: https://www.tinkercad.com/things/hFO8s3Lb0Ra-gopro-360-for-8-cameras

title: Lm8uu, dual fan mount x carriage for prusa

description.text: With PLA as my plastic of choice, I found that objects with short layer times benefitted greatly from a fan directly at the extruder. Greg Frost's Lm8uu X Carriage with Fan Mount fulfilled this requirement for most parts. However when printing thin layers with short layer times I found the side opposite the fan could still come out messy. To remedy this I added a fan to the other side.

Made to mount a 40mm fan on either side with m3 screws and nuts. 
This does increase the width of the X carriage by about 18mm if using a 10mm thick fan. I was able to move my build platform over to compensate without losing any build volume.

description.text:
Inspired by the work of AndrewBougie, I thought I'd have a go at creating a parametric version of a stylistically similar set of drawers, and learn how to use OpenSCAD at the same time.

Parameters

Basics Tab

These parameters are all in mm:

  1. Unit Depth: How deep the drawers are.
  2. Unit Width: How wide a single width drawer is.
  3. Unit Height: How tall a single height drawer is.
  4. Handle Thickness: The width of the handles.
  5. Handle Depth: How far the handles project from the front of the drawer
  6. Print Space: Free space to leave between print objects
  7. Wall: Thickness of the walls of the drawers and also the space between the drawers.
  8. Bevel: Length of the bevelled edge applied to the corners of the drawers.

Drawers Tab

These parameters have to be kept in sync, each is an array, and each element in the array describes a row of drawers

  1. Widths: Unit widths for each drawer in the row
  2. Heights: Unit heights for each drawer in the row
  3. Dividers: Number of dividers in each drawer of the row
  4. Handles: Number of handles on each drawer in the row

Example Drawer settings

Simple Drawers (Image 1)

You can replicate AndrewBougie's first design by using the following settings:

  1. Widths = [[1, 1], [2]]
  2. Heights = [[1, 1], [1]]
  3. Dividers = [[1, 1], [1]]
  4. Handles = [[1, 1], [2]]

As you can see each parameter's array has two sub-arrays, and each of these sub-arrays describes a single row of drawers in the final model.
Reading widths "[[1, 1], [2]]" we can then decode the meaning:
[1, 1]: two drawers on the first row, both being one unit wide
[2]: Only one drawer on the second row, but this one is two units wide.
Reading heights tells us that all drawers are a single unit high
Reading dividers tells us that all drawers have a single divider.
Finally, reading handles tells us the two drawers on the first row have a single handle each, and the wider drawer on the second row has two handles

Complex Drawers (Image 2)

Now you know what you are doing, you can get all super complex!

  1. Widths = [[1, 1, 1, 1], [2, 2], [4]]
  2. Heights = [[2, 2, 2, 2], [3, 3], [4]]
  3. Dividers = [[1, 0, 0, 1], [2, 2], [3]]
  4. Handles = [[1, 1, 1, 1], [2, 2], [2]]

Here we have 4 then 2 then 1 drawer on each of the rows.
The drawers get taller with each row 2 units, then 3 units then 4 units.
Two of the small drawers have no dividers, the other have a single divider, the double width drawers have 2 dividers, and the largest drawer has three dividers.
And finally, the small drawers all have a single handle, while all the bigger ones have two handles.

A Super Simple Single Drawer (Image 3)
  1. Widths = [[3]];
  2. Heights = [[4]];
  3. Dividers = [[1]];
  4. Handles = [[2]];

Printing tab (Images 4 & 5)

Allows you to examine parts of your print.

title: Filament guide tube holder for FlashForge Creator Pro 2016

description.text:
A week ago, I received my FlashForge Creator Pro 2016, and while I have been very impressed with this machine's performance, there are some things that could be improved.

For starters, it's very difficult to fit filament spools from other brands in the included spool holders, but that was easily solved by printing http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1001925

In a related note, the default position of the guide tubes is a bit awkward and it might allow the filament to tangle. So, I decided to print http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1055138

To my surprise... it doesn't fit on my machine. It seems that, in the 2016 version, the spacing between the clamps that hold the filament tubes was increased, and so I decided to re-make this design in SolidWorks.

After testing this design for a while, I decided to make a new one from scratch: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1557250

I strongly recommend the new design, as it looks better and it's easier to take off the printer bed!
